{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617379"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:13:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16466"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16466"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.04,0.04,0.16,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75530"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9157"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61045"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5061"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75530"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENoradrenaline (norepinephrine) is a neurotransmitter in the sympathetic nervous system. Its synthesis occurs within specialised nuclei in the brainstem through multiple enzymatic steps.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first step in noradrenaline synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA by tyrosine hydroxylase","Conversion of L-DOPA to dopamine","Conversion of dopamine to noradrenaline","Transport of tyrosine into neurons","Storage of noradrenaline in vesicles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first step in noradrenaline synthesis is the \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA by tyrosine hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E. This first step is also the rate-limiting step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion of L-DOPA to dopamine\u003C/strong\u003E is the second step in noradrenaline synthesis, catalysed by DOPA decarboxylase. It is followed by the \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion of dopamine to noradrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E, catalysed by dopamine \u03b2-hydroxylase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst necessary, the \u003Cstrong\u003Etransport of tyrosine into neurons \u003C/strong\u003Edescribes a transport rather than synthetic process. Similarly, the \u003Cstrong\u003Estorage of noradrenaline in vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E is a part of transport requirements but occurs after synthesis is complete.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Noradrenaline is synthesised from tyrosine through a series of enzymatic reactions.","The rate-limiting step in noradrenaline synthesis is the conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA by tyrosine hydroxylase."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Bylund DB. Norepinephrine. Reference Module in Biomedical Sciences. Published online 2016. doi:https://doi.org/10.1016/b978-0-12-801238-3.98841-x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61045"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16466"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61045"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T09:30:41+10:30","up